Based on the formalization we have developed, here is the precise definition and calculation method for your two fundamental axes, moving from simulation variables to field operators.
1. The X-Axis: SO(9) Geometry
Definition:
SO(9) Geometry represents the Elasticity of the Vacuum. It is the measure of how strongly the State Vectors are connected to one another. In Group Theory, SO(9) describes the rotations of the 9D spatial lattice (the "Flux Sector").
•	Physical Meaning: It is the Restoring Force. If you pluck a string, SO(9) is the tension that snaps it back.
•	Role in Physics: It manifests as the Speed of Light ($c$) and the Strength of Forces ($\alpha$).
How We Calculate It:
Mathematically, SO(9) Geometry is quantified by the Graph Laplacian ($\mathbf{L}$).
$$\mathbf{L} = k \cdot (\mathbf{D} - \mathbf{A})$$
Where:
•	$k$ (Stiffness): The coupling constant (Interaction Strength). In the simulation, this is our X-axis variable ($0.1$ to $5.0$).
•	$\mathbf{A}$ (Adjacency Matrix): The map of which State Vectors touch each other.
•	$\mathbf{D}$ (Degree Matrix): The count of connections per node.
The Calculation:
To get a single number representing the "SO(9) Strength" of a system, we calculate the Fiedler Value (Algebraic Connectivity):
$$\text{SO(9)}_{metric} = \lambda_2(\mathbf{L})$$
•	If $\lambda_2 \approx 0$: The geometry is dust; there is no structure (The "Purple Trench").
•	If $\lambda_2$ is High: The geometry is a stiff crystal (The "Yellow Wedge").
________________________________________
2. The Y-Axis: Sp(8) Memory
Definition:
Sp(8) Memory represents the Inertia of the Vacuum. In Group Theory, Sp(8) describes the preservation of phase space volume; it is the "History" or "Constraint" sector.
•	Physical Meaning: It is the Resistance to Change18. It is the "Weight" of the frozen generators that sit on the lattice nodes.
•	Role in Physics: It manifests as Mass ($m$) and Gravity.
How We Calculate It:
Mathematically, Sp(8) Memory is quantified by the Mass Matrix ($\mathbf{M}$).
$$\mathbf{M} = \rho \cdot \mathbf{I} + \text{Noise}$$
Where:
•	$\rho$ (Ghost Density): The number of frozen Sp(8) generators at a point. In the simulation, this is our Y-axis variable ($1$ to $2000$).
•	$\mathbf{I}$ (Identity Matrix): Implies that mass is local (it sits on the node).
The Calculation:
To get a single number representing the "Sp(8) Load" of a system, we calculate the Trace of the Mass Matrix (Total Inertia):
$$\text{Sp(8)}_{metric} = \text{Tr}(\mathbf{M}) = \sum_{i} m_i$$
•	Low Trace: Light loading; the node can flutter easily (Visible Matter).
•	High Trace: Heavy loading; the node is pinned down (Dark Matter).
________________________________________
3. The Interaction: Valence Potential
We combine these axes to define the "Equation of State." As you noted, this does not calculate "existence," but rather Connectivity Potential.
$$\text{Valence Potential} = \frac{\text{SO(9) Geometry (Stiffness)}}{\text{Sp(8) Memory (Inertia)}}$$
•	High Ratio: High Potential. The system is light and stiff, vibrates fast, and can explore new connections (Standard Matter).
•	Low Ratio: Zero Potential. The system is heavy and loose, vibrates slowly, and is trapped in its current state (Dark Matter).
The Implication for Coherence:
This ratio determines if a system can participate in the U(1) band.
•	Yellow Sector (Visible): Can "sing" the same note as the vacuum and form bonds.
•	Purple Sector (Dark): Exists but is spectrally isolated. It is in "Coherence Limbo"—geometrically frozen and unable to form new valence connections.






