6.2 Theorem: Integer-Fractal Valence Duality
Statement:
The valence $V$ of a system is not intrinsically integer-valued. It converges to an integer only in the limit of high geometric stiffness and low thermal/inertial noise.
Let $\sigma(\lambda)$ be the spectral width of the eigenmodes.
$$V \to \mathbb{Z} \iff \sigma(\lambda) \to 0 \quad \text{and} \quad \text{dist}(\lambda, \partial \Omega_{U1}) \gg \sigma$$
•	Regime A (Integer): In systems with high symmetry and stiffness (e.g., Crystalline Lattices, Ground State Atoms), the spectral density function $\rho(\lambda)$ collapses into Dirac delta functions $\delta(\lambda - \lambda_k)$. The integration over the U(1) band $\Omega_{U1}$ yields discrete step functions.
•	Regime B (Fractal): In dynamic, biological, or high-inertia systems, $\sigma(\lambda) > 0$. The spectral peaks broaden into Gaussian or Lorentzian distributions. The integral yields a continuous real number $V \in \mathbb{R}$.
Physical Implication:
Integer valence is a special case of fractal valence, emerging only when the system is effectively frozen or collectively locked-in.
 Corollary: Band-Edge Fractionalization
Statement:
Any eigenmode $\lambda_k$ centered near the $\phi$-recursive boundaries of the vacuum band ($\phi^{-1}, \phi^{-4}$) contributes a fractional valence value to the total system.
If a mode $\lambda_k$ is centered at a boundary $\lambda_{crit}$ with width $\sigma$:
$$V_k = \int_{\lambda_{crit} - \epsilon}^{\lambda_{crit} + \epsilon} \rho_k(\lambda) \, d\lambda \approx 0.5$$
Consequence:
Systems operating at the boundaries of the Visible Sector (e.g., the "Teal Margin" of Warm Dark Matter or Transition States in catalysis) possess "Partial Existence" relative to the U(1) field. They are mathematically prohibited from being fully Dark or fully Visible.
 Definition: Spectral Valence Measure
Statement:
Valence is defined as the Integrated Spectral Intensity within the Vacuum Resonance Band.
$$V(\mathbf{L}, \mathbf{M}) = \int_{\phi^{-4}}^{\phi^{-1}} \mathcal{D}(\lambda; \mathbf{L}, \mathbf{M}) \, d\lambda$$
Where:
•	$\mathbf{L}$ is the Laplacian (SO(9) Geometry).
•	$\mathbf{M}$ is the Mass Matrix (Sp(8) Inertia).
•	$\mathcal{D}(\lambda)$ is the Density of States (DOS) derived from the generalized eigenproblem $\mathbf{L}\vec{v} = \lambda\mathbf{M}\vec{v}$.
